00:55:27,534 --> 00:55:29,525
[ Grunting ]

499
00:55:31,654 --> 00:55:35,772
Don't ever touch
anything on my boat again.

500
00:55:39,054 --> 00:55:40,965
She said she was sorry!

501
00:55:44,814 --> 00:55:47,487
That means you're supposed
to say something back!

502
00:56:09,774 --> 00:56:11,685
- Did you say somethin'?
- [ Enola ] Mm-mmm.

503
00:56:34,494 --> 00:56:36,564
[ Deacon ] The child--
did he have the girl with him?

504
00:56:36,614 --> 00:56:38,809
- [ Pilot ] Uh-huh.
- Seems to me if we launch now,

505
00:56:38,894 --> 00:56:40,930
we can cut him down
just about here.

506
00:56:42,694 --> 00:56:45,925
- lf he doesn't change course.
- Ah, it's not likely.

507
00:56:46,014 --> 00:56:49,484
He's a wily one,
that ichthy-demon.

508
00:56:49,534 --> 00:56:52,048
Yeah, if he knows
he's been spotted,

509
00:56:52,094 --> 00:56:55,769
he'll expect us to expect him
to change course,

510
00:56:55,814 --> 00:56:59,250
which is exactly why
he'll keep his heading.

511
00:56:59,294 --> 00:57:02,411
The important question is,
where's he heading?

512
00:57:02,494 --> 00:57:05,884
And does he know
how precious his cargo is?

513
00:57:05,974 --> 00:57:10,172
l say that he's headed here,
and we take him here.

514
00:57:17,654 --> 00:57:20,805
[ Drifter Shouting ]

515
00:57:20,854 --> 00:57:22,970
- Drifter?
- Mm-hmm.

516
00:57:23,054 --> 00:57:24,885
- [ Shouting Continues ]
- [ Helen ] Are we gonna stop?

517
00:57:24,974 --> 00:57:26,805
- Look at the flag!
- His flag's up.

518
00:57:26,894 --> 00:57:28,885
l thought you all
stopped for each other.

519
00:57:33,974 --> 00:57:36,534
Well... maybe he has some food!

520
00:57:39,894 --> 00:57:42,408
Don't find many who follow
the rules anymore.

521
00:57:42,454 --> 00:57:45,173
Well, make it quick.
What's your business?

522
00:57:49,934 --> 00:57:51,845
Trade.

523
00:57:53,694 --> 00:57:55,605
You got any resin?

524
00:57:58,054 --> 00:58:02,013
Resin? He's gotta be out of
his mind. He's out of his mind.
l don't have any resin.

525
00:58:02,094 --> 00:58:04,449
- [ Babbling ]
- You been outwater
a long time, haven't you?

526
00:58:06,214 --> 00:58:08,523
Must be jokin' me, man.
Resin! You don't got enough.

527
00:58:08,614 --> 00:58:10,730
How 'bout food?

528
00:58:10,774 --> 00:58:12,730
Could you say that again, please?

529
00:58:12,814 --> 00:58:15,612
- How 'bout food?
- Ah, yeah, food.

530
00:58:15,694 --> 00:58:18,083
Yeah, that'd be good, eh?

531
00:58:18,134 --> 00:58:21,012
l haven't eaten in, well,
you know, forever.

532
00:58:22,214 --> 00:58:24,569
Which one of you two is a cook?

533
00:58:24,654 --> 00:58:28,169
'Cause l usually fall for the waitress.
[ Chuckling ]

534
00:58:28,254 --> 00:58:30,165
Like you said,
l don't have much.

535
00:58:30,254 --> 00:58:33,326
Now listen, eh? [ Mumbles ]
Let's see. What do l have to do?

536
00:58:33,414 --> 00:58:37,089
We can start with that wee orchard
you got over there.

537
00:58:37,134 --> 00:58:41,810
- [ Whooping ]
- All right, hold it there.

538
00:58:41,894 --> 00:58:45,170
- [ Mariner ] We can talk.
- [ Drifter ] Fair enough.

539
00:58:45,254 --> 00:58:48,087
[ Babbling ]

540
00:58:49,934 --> 00:58:52,209
lt's a nice rod, isn't it?

541
00:58:52,294 --> 00:58:55,206
l like that rod.
lt's a nice rod. [ Babbles ]

542
00:59:01,294 --> 00:59:03,967
Got yourself a wee harem
goin' here now, do ya?

543
00:59:10,294 --> 00:59:12,330
What you want for the women?

544
00:59:12,374 --> 00:59:14,683
We're not for sale.

545
00:59:14,734 --> 00:59:17,328
Not for sale?
There's no such thing as not for sale.

546
00:59:17,414 --> 00:59:19,564
"Not for sale"!
Not for sale, eh?

547
00:59:21,494 --> 00:59:24,850
- Are they a pair or would you
consider sellin' 'em separate?
- No.

548
00:59:24,934 --> 00:59:28,768
0ur business is done here unless you got
some resin for sale you can part with.

549
00:59:28,814 --> 00:59:30,691
l told you once already,
l don't have it.

550
00:59:30,734 --> 00:59:33,407
l-l-l don't have it.
Don't have it. Don't have it.

551
00:59:33,454 --> 00:59:37,447
Haven't seen neither for trade
in lunars now. Wait. Wait, wait, wait.

552
00:59:40,494 --> 00:59:42,724
l do have somethin' that'll
make you change your mind.

553
00:59:43,974 --> 00:59:47,444
Somethin' that you can't pass on.
[ Giggles ]

554
00:59:47,534 --> 00:59:51,652
l took it off
an Atoller refugee camp.

555
00:59:51,694 --> 00:59:53,571
The life savings
of the entire clan.

556
01:00:01,214 --> 01:00:04,092
Paper.
[ Babbles ]

557
01:00:04,174 --> 01:00:09,453
lt's paper. Have you ever
seen paper? Look at it.

558
01:00:09,494 --> 01:00:11,371
Smell it.

559
01:00:13,014 --> 01:00:15,050
l been savin' it
for a special trade.

560
01:00:18,054 --> 01:00:20,568
Don't you do it.

561
01:00:20,654 --> 01:00:23,407
You know, maybe l'm talkin'
to the wrong person here.

562
01:00:23,494 --> 01:00:25,564
Whose boat is this?
ls it your boat or your boat?

563
01:00:25,614 --> 01:00:29,129
No. No, it's his boat.
But he doesn't own us.

564
01:00:35,814 --> 01:00:37,770
Half an hour.

565
01:00:37,814 --> 01:00:41,250
[ Mumbling, Babbling ]
0ut of his mind somethin' there.

566
01:00:41,294 --> 01:00:45,128
l got two pages in here, man!
l mean, l'd get half a dozen
girls with this, you know.

567
01:00:45,174 --> 01:00:47,734
Half an hour.

568
01:00:47,814 --> 01:00:49,850
- You tradin' or not?
- Don't.

569
01:00:49,934 --> 01:00:51,811
Shut up.

570
01:00:53,294 --> 01:00:55,330
0kay.

571
01:00:56,854 --> 01:00:59,049
Forty-five minutes
with the wee one right there.

572
01:00:59,094 --> 01:01:01,449
l like to do the talkin',
if you know what l mean.

573
01:01:03,094 --> 01:01:04,971
No!

574
01:01:05,974 --> 01:01:08,932
Fair. Come, come,
come, come, come!

575
01:01:08,974 --> 01:01:11,249
No. My boat.

576
01:01:13,094 --> 01:01:16,370
- Fair enough. Fair enough.
Good, good, good. Aye.
- Helen.

577
01:01:16,454 --> 01:01:19,844
- Sit down.
- Enola, just do as he says.

578
01:01:21,974 --> 01:01:24,010
[ Chuckling ]

579
01:02:04,214 --> 01:02:07,092
lt's been a while for me now.

580
01:02:07,174 --> 01:02:10,610
Guess it's been
more than a while, actually.

581
01:02:13,654 --> 01:02:18,409
l've only got half an hour.
[ Repeating ] Half an hour,
half an hour, half an hour--

582
01:02:19,454 --> 01:02:21,285
[ Mumbles ]
Great, great, great--

583
01:02:21,374 --> 01:02:25,925
[ Gasps ] 0oh! You're so beautiful.
Aye! Anyone ever told you that?

584
01:02:26,014 --> 01:02:28,812
Give me that. What are you doin'?
lt's just a game.

585
01:02:32,094 --> 01:02:34,927
0h, l, um-- l, uh--
We was just playin'.

586
01:02:37,934 --> 01:02:39,890
The trade's off.

587
01:02:39,974 --> 01:02:41,771
l changed my mind.

588
01:02:42,774 --> 01:02:45,652
Well, um-- Well,
you can't do that.

589
01:02:45,734 --> 01:02:48,089
l mean, a deal's a deal, eh?

590
01:02:48,174 --> 01:02:49,926
l just did.

591
01:02:50,414 --> 01:02:52,132
Hey!

592
01:02:52,174 --> 01:02:56,531
She's mine. Aye. No. No, no
l own her. But-- No.

593
01:02:56,614 --> 01:02:59,367
- Go on.
- Get, get, get.
Go, go, go. Good, good.

594
01:02:59,454 --> 01:03:03,686
But don't go too far now.
This won't take but a minute.

595
01:03:08,574 --> 01:03:13,728
l hate this boat.
l hate this boat!

596
01:03:13,774 --> 01:03:16,368
You bastard.

597
01:03:20,414 --> 01:03:25,124
You-- You're pretty stingy for a man
who's got everything, aren't ya now?

598
01:03:28,854 --> 01:03:30,970
0h-h-h. 0hh.

599
01:03:37,694 --> 01:03:41,050
- [ Yells ]
- [ Crashing ]

600
01:03:41,134 --> 01:03:43,170
[ Drifter ]
Ah, you bastard!

601
01:03:43,214 --> 01:03:45,728
[ Banging, Crashing Continue ]

602
01:03:54,094 --> 01:03:56,050
Where's me boat?

603
01:03:57,294 --> 01:03:59,330
Where's me boat?

604
01:03:59,374 --> 01:04:03,287
[ Mumbling ]

605
01:04:06,334 --> 01:04:08,165
Help me to me boat.

606
01:04:09,654 --> 01:04:11,531
0w! Me boat.

607
01:04:13,614 --> 01:04:15,411
Me boat.

608
01:04:43,214 --> 01:04:45,045
[ Helen ]
What the-- No!

609
01:04:47,374 --> 01:04:49,569
Never catch anything
with this. lt's useless.

610
01:04:51,374 --> 01:04:53,205
[ Helen Gasps ]

611
01:04:55,174 --> 01:04:59,486
Look, l'm sorry.
You were right about the pole.

612
01:05:00,774 --> 01:05:03,129
You were right,
but we have to eat.

613
01:05:08,614 --> 01:05:10,525
Now l know
you can hear me!

614
01:05:10,574 --> 01:05:13,930
Now we can fish for ourselves.
You show us what to do.

615
01:05:13,974 --> 01:05:16,169
You must know how.
Even you gotta eat!

616
01:05:16,214 --> 01:05:18,489
You just sit there.

617
01:05:41,134 --> 01:05:43,967
- What--
- [ Mumbling ] l don't know.

618
01:06:18,334 --> 01:06:20,165
Happy now?

619
01:06:24,294 --> 01:06:28,685
--[ Humming ]

620
01:06:28,774 --> 01:06:33,848
--[ Humming Continues ]

621
01:06:37,614 --> 01:06:39,445
You don't like my singing,
do you?

622
01:06:42,254 --> 01:06:46,133
Helen says you don't like my singing
'cause you can't sing.

623
01:06:51,974 --> 01:06:54,568
- Ever try and listen?
- To what?

624
01:06:57,534 --> 01:06:59,684
The sound of the world.

625
01:07:03,694 --> 01:07:06,492
- l don't hear anything.
- That's because you're too loud,

626
01:07:06,574 --> 01:07:08,405
and you're movin' around
all the time.

627
01:07:08,494 --> 01:07:11,133
Try sittin' still.

628
01:07:11,214 --> 01:07:14,092
Eyeball?

629
01:07:27,894 --> 01:07:29,850
l wish l had feet like his.

630
01:07:32,814 --> 01:07:34,611
Then maybe l could swim.

631
01:07:34,694 --> 01:07:36,286
Enola.

632
01:07:39,814 --> 01:07:41,805
[ Burps ] Sorry.

633
01:07:46,334 --> 01:07:48,689
Never met a person
couldn't swim before.

634
01:07:51,374 --> 01:07:54,093
l can't.

635
01:07:55,294 --> 01:07:57,489
People say l was weird.

636
01:07:57,574 --> 01:07:59,405
Maybe they were right.

637
01:08:02,814 --> 01:08:05,123
Maybe they were right
about you too.

638
01:08:31,854 --> 01:08:33,731
Enola wanted to give you this.

639
01:08:37,854 --> 01:08:40,368
And this.

640
01:08:42,414 --> 01:08:44,450
She won't take it again.

641
01:08:50,614 --> 01:08:53,447
You don't look much like her.

642
01:08:53,494 --> 01:08:57,373
- Well, l'm not her mother,
if that's what you're asking.
- You act like it.

643
01:09:00,974 --> 01:09:03,090
What are those marks
on her back?

644
01:09:03,174 --> 01:09:05,734
Nothing.
They're just fanciful things.

645
01:09:06,974 --> 01:09:10,933
- Like what she draws?
- She draws what she sees.

646
01:09:11,014 --> 01:09:13,733
She's like a mirror.

647
01:09:13,774 --> 01:09:15,765
People on the atoll
thought she was a--

648
01:09:17,454 --> 01:09:20,093
Freak?

649
01:09:20,174 --> 01:09:22,449
Uh-huh. Yeah.

650
01:09:22,534 --> 01:09:24,411
l just thought
she was special.

651
01:09:31,814 --> 01:09:35,443
l'm not givin' it
to her. lt's just--

652
01:09:35,534 --> 01:09:37,206
A loan.

653
01:09:37,294 --> 01:09:40,127
Yeah. l'm not
givin' it to her.

654
01:09:45,694 --> 01:09:48,766
ls Dryland beautiful?

655
01:09:50,254 --> 01:09:52,484
You'll see.

656
01:10:09,574 --> 01:10:14,284
[ Enola Laughing, Giggling ]

657
01:10:17,214 --> 01:10:19,523
- Enola?
- [ Laughing ]

658
01:10:19,614 --> 01:10:21,525
Enola, what are you doing?

659
01:10:21,614 --> 01:10:24,890
- Those monsters'll kill her!
- No, they're asleep now.

660
01:10:27,814 --> 01:10:29,850
Hands around my neck.

661
01:10:31,814 --> 01:10:34,169
Let the water tell your arms
and legs how to move.

662
01:10:34,254 --> 01:10:36,324
We're goin' down.
Hold your breath.

663
01:12:11,774 --> 01:12:14,652
- What is it?
- What is it?

664
01:12:16,654 --> 01:12:18,645
Barter outpost.

665
01:12:18,734 --> 01:12:20,611
You said we'd get
to Dryland today.

666
01:12:20,654 --> 01:12:23,691
Today. Tomorrow.
What's it matter?

667
01:12:25,254 --> 01:12:27,085
l need resin.

668
01:12:36,334 --> 01:12:41,533
- What is that?
- lt's PortuGreek. Their own language.

669
01:12:44,374 --> 01:12:46,604
0r so l thought.

670
01:13:11,974 --> 01:13:14,124
Ah.

671
01:13:14,214 --> 01:13:17,411
There's my girl. Yeah.

672
01:13:17,454 --> 01:13:20,969
Howdy, darlin'.
Come on in here now.

673
01:13:49,294 --> 01:13:51,569
- What's going on?
- Smokers.

674
01:13:54,854 --> 01:13:56,685
What the hell?

675
01:14:00,134 --> 01:14:02,932
He's spotted us.
Sound it!

676
01:14:03,014 --> 01:14:06,689
Sound it! Sound it!
Sound it! Sound it!

677
01:14:17,294 --> 01:14:19,762
Yahoo!

678
01:14:27,254 --> 01:14:30,212
[ Helen ] Enola!

679
01:14:38,414 --> 01:14:41,167
- [ Bullets Whizzing By ]
- [ Grunting ]

680
01:14:41,254 --> 01:14:43,165
Starboard side! Now!

681
01:14:44,174 --> 01:14:46,051
Get in the chair!

682
01:14:52,134 --> 01:14:54,887
Watch it.
He's clearin' the net.

683
01:15:05,814 --> 01:15:07,884
Go to the helm.

684
01:15:09,614 --> 01:15:11,889
- Get the centerboard!
- Centerboard?

685
01:15:11,974 --> 01:15:14,613
What centerboard?
l don't know what to do!

686
01:15:17,134 --> 01:15:19,090
lt's too late.
0ver here!

687
01:15:31,574 --> 01:15:35,044
[ Screaming, Yelling ]

688
01:15:37,894 --> 01:15:39,771
No!

689
01:15:55,374 --> 01:16:00,050
Gimme that rifle.
Boy, if you wanna do somethin' right,

690
01:16:00,134 --> 01:16:02,694
you've got to do it yourself.

691
01:16:02,734 --> 01:16:04,611
[ Whispers ]
All right.

692
01:16:10,894 --> 01:16:12,771
- l winged him.
- l say we load...

693
01:16:12,814 --> 01:16:15,851
all the go-juice onto one boat
and run the freak down.

694
01:16:15,934 --> 01:16:19,085
You can't catch him in ten boats,
and you wanna send just one?

695
01:16:19,174 --> 01:16:21,688
Well, l pray that you're jokin'.

696
01:16:29,774 --> 01:16:32,686
Bring me the trackers.

697
01:16:37,254 --> 01:16:39,609
He's hurt.

698
01:16:39,694 --> 01:16:41,924
lt's not what you think.
They weren't after her.

699
01:16:42,014 --> 01:16:44,528
- l saw what l saw.
- What?

700
01:16:48,734 --> 01:16:50,565
No more lies.

701
01:16:52,014 --> 01:16:55,086
- [ Shrieks ]
- What are the marks on her back?

702
01:16:55,174 --> 01:16:57,734
People say it's the way to Dryland.

703
01:16:57,774 --> 01:17:00,288
Dryland's a myth!

704
01:17:00,334 --> 01:17:03,246
No! You said so yourself
that you know where it is.

705
01:17:03,334 --> 01:17:05,165
You did.

706
01:17:09,214 --> 01:17:12,286
You're a fool to believe in something
you've never seen before.

707
01:17:12,334 --> 01:17:16,612
l've seen it. l've touched it!
Dirt that was richer
and darker than yours.

708
01:17:16,654 --> 01:17:18,485
lt was in the basket
we found Enola in!

709
01:17:18,574 --> 01:17:21,088
- lt doesn't exist!
- Well, how can you be so sure?

710
01:17:21,134 --> 01:17:25,685
Because l've sailed farther than most
have dreamed, and l've never seen it.

711
01:17:27,534 --> 01:17:30,253
But the things on your boat!

712
01:17:30,294 --> 01:17:32,603
"Things on my boat" what?

713
01:17:32,654 --> 01:17:35,964
There are things on your boat
that nobody has ever seen!

714
01:17:36,014 --> 01:17:38,084
What are these shells?

715
01:17:38,174 --> 01:17:41,166
And that reflecting glass?

716
01:17:41,254 --> 01:17:45,452
And th-the music box?
That--

717
01:17:45,494 --> 01:17:49,043
Well, if not from Dryland,
then where? Wh-Where?

718
01:17:51,814 --> 01:17:53,691
You wanna see Dryland?

719
01:17:55,334 --> 01:17:57,165
You really wanna see it?

720
01:17:58,774 --> 01:18:00,765
l'll take you to Dryland.

721
01:18:07,814 --> 01:18:09,645
Get in.

722
01:18:15,374 --> 01:18:18,411
- Well, what about Enola?
- There's only air for one.

723
01:18:18,454 --> 01:18:20,684
- Get in the water.
- lt'll be all right.

724
01:18:26,094 --> 01:18:28,085
Don't touch anything.

725
01:18:32,654 --> 01:18:34,531
0kay?

726
01:21:56,974 --> 01:21:58,851
l didn't know.

727
01:22:00,614 --> 01:22:03,492
All this time...

728
01:22:03,534 --> 01:22:05,411
l didn't know.

729
01:22:05,454 --> 01:22:07,331
Nobody does.

730
01:22:15,054 --> 01:22:16,965
Can you get us outta here?

731
01:22:17,014 --> 01:22:20,370
l'd say there're
two chances o' that.

732
01:22:20,454 --> 01:22:22,763
- Hey!
- No way and no how.

733
01:22:22,854 --> 01:22:26,403
Shoulda bought me
that drink. Come on!

734
01:22:26,494 --> 01:22:28,212
This way. Come on!

735
01:22:28,294 --> 01:22:32,924
[ Men Yelling, Cheering ]

736
01:22:34,694 --> 01:22:36,844
Proper introductions first.

737
01:22:37,934 --> 01:22:40,289
l'm the Deacon.

738
01:22:40,334 --> 01:22:44,373
[ Men Laughing ]

739
01:22:44,454 --> 01:22:48,970
lf you don't recall the face,
perhaps it's 'cause l didn't
always look like this.

740
01:22:51,974 --> 01:22:55,444
Now, ahem, l suspect
she's somewhere real close.

741
01:22:55,534 --> 01:23:01,131
So we can tear this boat apart
lookin' for her, but l'd rather
somebody tell me where she is.

742
01:23:01,214 --> 01:23:03,933
And the first one
that does that, lives.

743
01:23:04,014 --> 01:23:08,212
And the runner-up--
Well, actually, there are no runners-up.

744
01:23:10,734 --> 01:23:13,248
0h, sweet Joe,
l love this part.

745
01:23:13,294 --> 01:23:16,047
Choose 'em. 0ne, two.
Live or die.

746
01:23:17,494 --> 01:23:20,531
You know, personally,

747
01:23:20,614 --> 01:23:23,412
l'd rather shoot
the sperm-of-the-devil here.

748
01:23:23,494 --> 01:23:26,566
Huh? But you know somethin'?

749
01:23:26,654 --> 01:23:29,043
l don't think you're gonna
tell me, are ya?

750
01:23:29,134 --> 01:23:30,965
Huh? Too bad.

751
01:23:32,054 --> 01:23:35,410
Come on, eh?
What do you say?

752
01:23:35,494 --> 01:23:37,325
She's not your kind.

753
01:23:38,734 --> 01:23:41,123
You don't even have a kind.

754
01:23:41,214 --> 01:23:45,173
lf you say it,
he'll still kill us both.

755
01:23:45,254 --> 01:23:48,212
[ Deacon Grunts ]

756
01:23:49,334 --> 01:23:51,211
Let's not get ahead of ourselves.

757
01:23:53,134 --> 01:23:55,011
lf you don't tell me,

758
01:23:55,054 --> 01:23:57,522
l swear to Poseidon
l will torch your boat.

759
01:24:03,854 --> 01:24:07,210
Refresh my memory.
What happens when neither of 'em talks?

760
01:24:07,254 --> 01:24:09,973
- Never happened before.
- Never happened before.

761
01:24:10,054 --> 01:24:12,568
[ Sighs ]
All right!

762
01:24:12,654 --> 01:24:17,523
lf they won't tell us where
she is, do 'em! Both of 'em!
Kill 'em now! [ Fires Gun ]

763
01:24:17,614 --> 01:24:20,367
- No!
- [ Helen ] No!

764
01:24:20,454 --> 01:24:22,285
So gullible!
Bring her here.

765
01:24:22,374 --> 01:24:24,683
[ Men Cheering, Shouting ]

766
01:24:24,774 --> 01:24:27,368
- Take and ye shall receive!
- [ Helen ] No! Leave her!

767
01:24:27,454 --> 01:24:30,014
So ends your daily sermonette!
[ Laughing ]

768
01:24:30,094 --> 01:24:33,769
All we gotta do is figure out this map.
Turn her upside down.

769
01:24:33,854 --> 01:24:37,051
- Does that mean anything to you?
- No.

770
01:24:37,134 --> 01:24:40,490
[ Deacon ] We'll figure it out back
at the 'Deez. Back at the 'Deez, boys.

771
01:24:40,574 --> 01:24:42,804
Careful with her.
Careful with her!

772
01:24:42,894 --> 01:24:44,691
- What about them?
- Do 'em both.

773
01:24:44,774 --> 01:24:47,242
Torch the boat.

774
01:24:50,574 --> 01:24:53,372
We have to go under!

775
01:24:54,454 --> 01:24:57,207
No, l can't breath like you!

776
01:24:57,294 --> 01:24:59,125
l'll breathe for both of us.

777
01:25:22,734 --> 01:25:24,611
[ Man ] Whoo!

778
01:25:24,654 --> 01:25:26,531
[ Enola ] Helen!

779
01:25:28,494 --> 01:25:33,807
Helen, help!
Helen! Helen!

780
01:26:03,694 --> 01:26:05,571
My boat.

781
01:26:14,614 --> 01:26:16,491
Enola.

782
01:26:16,534 --> 01:26:18,684
[ Door 0pens ]

783
01:26:18,734 --> 01:26:21,453
What is this?
Get those chains off her.

784
01:26:21,534 --> 01:26:24,332
What are we, barbarians here?

785
01:26:24,414 --> 01:26:26,723
Goodness gracious.
Sakes alive.

786
01:26:26,774 --> 01:26:29,129
Come on. 0utta here,
you big, nasty animal, you!

787
01:26:30,734 --> 01:26:33,043
Well, rub-a-dub-dub.
[ Chuckles ]

788
01:26:34,894 --> 01:26:38,125
You wanna come over here
and sit on my lap?

789
01:26:38,214 --> 01:26:40,808
No? Ahem.

790
01:26:40,894 --> 01:26:43,772
How 'bout a cigarette?

791
01:26:43,854 --> 01:26:47,130
Nothin' like a good smoke
if you miss your mom.

792
01:26:47,214 --> 01:26:49,045
Never too young to start.

793
01:26:50,614 --> 01:26:53,845
No. Well, l got somethin'
right here l know you'd like.

794
01:26:55,534 --> 01:26:57,968
Like to draw, don't you? Huh?

795
01:26:59,894 --> 01:27:03,933
Huh?
Now they're yours...

796
01:27:04,014 --> 01:27:08,087
if you help me with just
one problem, all right?

797
01:27:10,974 --> 01:27:14,410
Now, ahem-- Now that tattoo
on your back-- Ahem.

798
01:27:16,054 --> 01:27:20,332
l've been told that, uh--
that's actually a map?

799
01:27:23,374 --> 01:27:25,649
lt's the way to Dryland.

800
01:27:25,734 --> 01:27:27,565
Now we're gettin' someplace.

801
01:27:29,294 --> 01:27:31,967
Could you teach me
how to read that?

802
01:27:34,734 --> 01:27:36,611
Setback.

803
01:27:38,734 --> 01:27:42,693
Well, have you ever heard
any of your friends talk about it?

804
01:27:42,734 --> 01:27:47,683
You know, like your mommy or
your pet fish? Did he say anything?

805
01:27:47,734 --> 01:27:50,089
You shouldn't make fun of him.
He wouldn't like it.

806
01:27:50,134 --> 01:27:55,333
Girl, l don't give a shit
what he'd like. He took out my eye.

807
01:27:55,374 --> 01:28:01,085
And if l ever see him again, l'm gonna
cut open his head and eat his brains!

808
01:28:01,134 --> 01:28:03,284
You think he'd like that?

809
01:28:03,374 --> 01:28:06,969
Can't kill him.
He's even meaner than you are.

810
01:28:08,014 --> 01:28:10,084
But he's not here.

811
01:28:10,134 --> 01:28:12,011
And he ain't comin'.

812
01:28:12,054 --> 01:28:13,851
And no one's gonna save you.

813
01:28:15,214 --> 01:28:17,045
He'll come for me. He will.

814
01:28:17,134 --> 01:28:21,013
Then you better tell me what l wanna
know or he can see what's left of you...

815
01:28:21,094 --> 01:28:23,164
in a goddamn jar.

816
01:28:33,054 --> 01:28:35,329
We're going to die here,
aren't we?

817
01:28:54,414 --> 01:28:56,245
Aren't we?

818
01:29:05,294 --> 01:29:07,888
After the atoll,

819
01:29:07,974 --> 01:29:10,534
when l offered myself to you,

820
01:29:13,014 --> 01:29:15,369
why didn't you take me?

821
01:29:17,174 --> 01:29:19,051
'Cause you didn't really want me.

822
01:29:20,934 --> 01:29:23,812
Not really.

823
01:31:14,814 --> 01:31:17,044
Have l been asleep long?

824
01:31:22,534 --> 01:31:24,365
l was dreaming.

825
01:31:26,774 --> 01:31:29,652
lt's funny.

826
01:31:29,734 --> 01:31:32,328
l always thought Dryland floated.

827
01:31:32,414 --> 01:31:35,690
That it drifted with the wind.
That's why it was so hard to find.

828
01:31:35,734 --> 01:31:37,929
Why did you believe in it so much?

829
01:31:39,174 --> 01:31:41,608
Because we weren't made for the sea.

830
01:31:42,894 --> 01:31:46,011
Got hands... and feet.

831
01:31:46,094 --> 01:31:48,608
We're supposed to walk.

832
01:31:51,534 --> 01:31:53,365
l miss her sound.

833
01:31:55,814 --> 01:31:57,645
Don't you?

834
01:32:01,014 --> 01:32:02,811
[ Gregor ] Helen!

835
01:32:02,894 --> 01:32:05,931
He-- No, no, no.
Helen, up here. Above you!

836
01:32:05,974 --> 01:32:08,442
- [ Chuckling ]
- [ Helen ] Gregor!

837
01:32:08,494 --> 01:32:12,533
[ Chuckling Continues ]

838
01:32:12,614 --> 01:32:15,253
Smart thinking
to burn your boat.

839
01:32:15,334 --> 01:32:18,929
Without the smoke,
l never would have found you.

840
01:32:19,014 --> 01:32:20,970
Who's that with you?

841
01:32:21,014 --> 01:32:24,563
lchthyus Sapien,
is that really you?

842
01:32:24,654 --> 01:32:28,442
l'll throw the rope down.
You catch it. l'll help you climb up.

843
01:32:30,574 --> 01:32:33,930
Helen. Where's Enola?

844
01:32:33,974 --> 01:32:39,173
Smokers took her. They'd have me too
if it weren't for him.

845
01:32:39,214 --> 01:32:43,253
My friend, thank you.
Very human of you.

846
01:32:45,134 --> 01:32:47,694
Go grab your things quickly.
Quickly. Come.

847
01:32:55,254 --> 01:32:57,210
[ Gregor ] You see?
Right down there.

848
01:32:57,294 --> 01:33:00,172
There's several of us survivors.
We'll just start over again.

849
01:33:02,134 --> 01:33:04,011
[ Man ] You can't ask us
to go get her!

850
01:33:04,054 --> 01:33:06,204
[ Woman ] Enola's the reason
we're in all this trouble.

851
01:33:06,254 --> 01:33:10,850
[ Helen ] They don't have any
reason to kill her. They need
to find Dryland just like we do.

852
01:33:10,894 --> 01:33:14,728
- 0f course.
- [ Helen ] lf the Mariner's
willing to go, why not us?

853
01:33:14,774 --> 01:33:16,810
[ Woman ]
lf he wants to go, then let him!

854
01:33:16,854 --> 01:33:19,971
[ Woman #2 ] We don't want you here!
You or the girl!

855
01:33:20,014 --> 01:33:24,292
Helen. The papers
the Mariner brought you--

856
01:33:24,334 --> 01:33:28,805
lt's the same language the tattoo
is written in. They're numbers.

857
01:33:28,854 --> 01:33:32,005
- [ Man ] Gregor,
you're as crazy as she is!
- [ Woman ] We can't stay here!

858
01:33:32,094 --> 01:33:35,530
We're wasting valuable time.
More Smokers will come.
We need to be moving now!

859
01:33:35,614 --> 01:33:39,812
My friends, don't you see we need
this child if we want to find Dryland?

860
01:33:39,854 --> 01:33:41,765
- l'm not goin'.
- Nobody is.

861
01:33:41,814 --> 01:33:44,123
[ Woman ] We've seen their smoke
on the horizon!

862
01:33:44,174 --> 01:33:46,847
- Know what that is yet?
- The numbers? Yes, l think l do.

863
01:33:46,894 --> 01:33:52,207
lt seems to be some ancient form
of geographic location:
latitude, longitude.

864
01:33:52,294 --> 01:33:56,924
lt doesn't make sense, though.
The numbers, they seem
to be backwards or something.

865
01:33:56,974 --> 01:33:59,044
- lt's upside down.
- The world?

866
01:33:59,134 --> 01:34:01,648
The poles have reversed themselves?

867
01:34:01,734 --> 01:34:03,884
l've been mappin' the cities below.

868
01:34:06,574 --> 01:34:09,850
The world wasn't created in a deluge.
lt was covered by it.

869
01:34:09,934 --> 01:34:13,006
- [ Man ] That's blasphemy!
- [ Helen ] No, it's true.

870
01:34:13,094 --> 01:34:17,610
l've seen it with
my own eyes. There is land.
lt's right under our keel.

871
01:34:17,654 --> 01:34:19,690
- None of it's dry anymore.
- Some is.

872
01:34:21,094 --> 01:34:25,485
Enola's been there.
l know that now. l saw what she drew.

873
01:34:25,574 --> 01:34:29,249
So that's why he's going after Enola--
to find Dryland.

874
01:34:29,294 --> 01:34:31,888
l don't care about Dryland.

875
01:34:31,974 --> 01:34:34,693
This is ridiculous.
Going after the Smokers?

876
01:34:34,734 --> 01:34:36,929
He doesn't even know
which direction they came from.

877
01:34:36,974 --> 01:34:41,604
- [ Man ] l say let him go.
- [ Woman ] We're better off
without them anyway!

878
01:34:41,694 --> 01:34:45,289
lf she's alive,
l'll bring her back to you.

879
01:34:45,334 --> 01:34:49,771
[ Woman ] Forget the mute-o, Helen.
lf he brings her back, they'll kill us!

880
01:34:49,814 --> 01:34:53,329
l can't stand it. We gotta go help him.
l can't ask him to do this alone.

881
01:34:53,414 --> 01:34:57,293
0h, don't worry, my dear.
You're not going to have to.

882
01:35:03,134 --> 01:35:05,967
[ Deacon ] You got that tattoo
figured out yet?

883
01:35:06,014 --> 01:35:08,528
lt would be easier if it was flat--
big and flat.

884
01:35:08,574 --> 01:35:11,327
- lt needs to be flat.
- What you got in mind?

885
01:35:11,414 --> 01:35:15,566
Well, you cut it off her back.
You stretch it, mount it.

886
01:35:15,614 --> 01:35:19,129
- Give us a proper look.
- Take her down below until l holler.

887
01:35:19,214 --> 01:35:21,364
Saint Joe, we're close.

888
01:35:23,534 --> 01:35:25,764
After centuries of shame.

889
01:36:00,414 --> 01:36:02,370
[ Scraping ]

890
01:36:09,854 --> 01:36:12,687
[ Distant Shouting ]

891
01:36:42,974 --> 01:36:46,364
[ Distant Laughter ]

892
01:36:49,094 --> 01:36:52,404
[ Crowd Shouting ]

893
01:36:52,454 --> 01:36:55,969
- They're gettin' ugly.
- Don't l know it.

894
01:36:56,054 --> 01:36:58,010
Announce me, cousin.

895
01:36:59,654 --> 01:37:01,849
[ Crowd Chanting ]

896
01:37:01,894 --> 01:37:03,930
- [ Microphone Popping ]
- Hey. Here he is.

897
01:37:03,974 --> 01:37:05,851
[ Crowd ] Deacon!

898
01:37:05,894 --> 01:37:08,328
Rise up, brothers and sisters.

899
01:37:09,934 --> 01:37:13,210
Turn your eyes and open your hearts...

900
01:37:13,294 --> 01:37:15,603
to your humble benefactor,

901
01:37:15,694 --> 01:37:19,403
your spiritual shepherd
and dictator for life,

902
01:37:19,454 --> 01:37:22,332
the Deacon of the 'Deez.

903
01:37:22,414 --> 01:37:25,212
[ Crowd Cheering ]

904
01:37:38,414 --> 01:37:40,803
[ Cheering Continues ]

905
01:37:43,014 --> 01:37:46,006
- Look out!
- lt's mine! lt's mine!

906
01:37:46,094 --> 01:37:48,369
[ Confused Shouting ]

907
01:37:52,414 --> 01:37:55,611
- Deacon!
- Wahoo!

908
01:37:55,694 --> 01:38:01,212
Children.
Children of the provider.

909
01:38:01,294 --> 01:38:05,003
Citizens of the good ship.
Please now, hear me speak.

910
01:38:08,854 --> 01:38:11,812
- l've had a vision.
- [ Man ] Yeah, we're
tired of your visions!

911
01:38:11,894 --> 01:38:14,169
What about the land
you promised us?

912
01:38:14,214 --> 01:38:16,887
[ Crowd ]
Yeah! Yeah!

913
01:38:16,934 --> 01:38:19,050
[ Deacon ]
0 ye of little faith.

914
01:38:19,134 --> 01:38:21,284
l've had a vision so great...

915
01:38:21,374 --> 01:38:24,605
that as it came to me, l wept.

916
01:38:24,694 --> 01:38:28,653
- And in this splenditudinous
figment of wonder,
- ls that Bone's ride?

917
01:38:28,734 --> 01:38:30,725
- ls that blood on the seat?
- l saw--

918
01:38:30,814 --> 01:38:34,489
And you know
what it is that l saw.

919
01:38:34,574 --> 01:38:38,328
l saw... the land.

920
01:38:38,374 --> 01:38:41,252
[ Cheering ]

921
01:38:48,214 --> 01:38:51,604
[ Gasping ]

922
01:39:02,494 --> 01:39:04,564
[ Crowd Chanting ]

923
01:39:10,054 --> 01:39:12,124
- Horse, that you?
- [ Engine Revving ]

924
01:39:16,614 --> 01:39:19,606
Look, just bring it in slow,
okay? l don't have all day.

925
01:39:19,694 --> 01:39:22,925
- [ Engine Revs ]
- Horse!

926
01:39:22,974 --> 01:39:25,363
Just bring it up slow.

927
01:39:26,454 --> 01:39:29,207
l said slow!
[ Screams ]

928
01:39:33,814 --> 01:39:37,648
Shouldn't be doing that.
You're gonna get in trouble.

929
01:39:37,694 --> 01:39:39,889
Ha. That's right.

930
01:39:39,934 --> 01:39:43,813
You're not afraid. You've got
your pet freak comin' to rescue you.

931
01:39:43,894 --> 01:39:48,251
He's not a freak,
and he can take you anytime.

932
01:39:48,334 --> 01:39:52,247
He's killed dozens of people, and he
doesn't have any mercy or anything.

933
01:39:52,334 --> 01:39:54,370
He even kills little girls.

934
01:39:56,174 --> 01:39:57,687
Haven't we all?

935
01:39:59,694 --> 01:40:01,605
Shit.

936
01:40:01,694 --> 01:40:03,764
lt's Horse.

937
01:40:05,054 --> 01:40:07,443
- Find him. Find him!
- Come on!

938
01:40:07,534 --> 01:40:11,652
- [ Crowd Chanting ]
- Yes! Yes! Yes!

939
01:40:11,734 --> 01:40:15,249
- Come on.
- Gettin' nervous, aren't you?

940
01:40:19,374 --> 01:40:21,205
l don't get nervous.

941
01:40:22,494 --> 01:40:24,883
[ Deacon ]
And if there's a river, we'll dam it.

942
01:40:24,974 --> 01:40:29,252
And if there's a tree,
we'll ram it.

943
01:40:29,334 --> 01:40:32,326
'Cause l'm talkin' progress here.

944
01:40:32,414 --> 01:40:35,292
Yes, sir. l'm talkin' development.

945
01:40:35,374 --> 01:40:39,253
- [ Man ] Yeah!
- For we shall suck and savor...

946
01:40:39,294 --> 01:40:43,572
the sweet flavor of Dryland.

947
01:40:43,614 --> 01:40:45,411
- [ Crowd Whistling ]
- [ Enola ] Face is all red.

948
01:40:45,494 --> 01:40:50,363
- [ Deacon Continues Faintly ]
- Helen said with anybody
that has a face that red,

949
01:40:50,454 --> 01:40:52,524
he's had too much sun
or too much to drink.

950
01:40:52,574 --> 01:40:56,533
- All right, that's it.
l'm gonna burn your face.
- Almost time.

951
01:40:56,574 --> 01:41:00,533
- [ Clanging ]
- What's up?
- We're just talkin' about our friend.

952
01:41:02,774 --> 01:41:05,527
- [ Doctor ] What's his name?
- [ Enola ] He doesn't have a name.

953
01:41:05,574 --> 01:41:08,088
So death can't find him.

954
01:41:08,134 --> 01:41:10,011
Nah-nah.

955
01:41:13,134 --> 01:41:16,888
Doesn't have a home
or people to care for.

956
01:41:16,974 --> 01:41:19,772
He's not afraid of anything,
men least of all.

957
01:41:19,854 --> 01:41:23,324
He's fast and strong
like a big wind.

958
01:41:23,414 --> 01:41:26,486
He can hear a hundred miles
and see a hundred miles underwater.

959
01:41:26,574 --> 01:41:30,453
- [ Gagging ]
- He can hide in the shadow
of the noon sun.

960
01:41:30,494 --> 01:41:34,248
He could be right behind you, and you
won't even know it 'til you're dead!

961
01:41:36,734 --> 01:41:38,645
Give it a rest.

962
01:41:39,894 --> 01:41:41,850
He'll come for me. He will.

963
01:41:41,894 --> 01:41:44,408
- [ Deacon Addressing Crowd ]
We are the people--
- Yeah?

964
01:41:44,454 --> 01:41:47,764
- Well, l hope he does.
- [ Deacon ] The Lord's creation.

965
01:41:49,014 --> 01:41:50,845
Remember you said that.

966
01:41:51,934 --> 01:41:54,607
[ Deacon Continues ]
Look at us.

967
01:41:54,654 --> 01:41:57,214
- Look at us here today.
- [ Man ] Yeah!

968
01:41:57,254 --> 01:42:00,724
Dryland is not just
our destination,

969
01:42:00,814 --> 01:42:02,805
but it is our destiny!

970
01:42:02,894 --> 01:42:05,089
[ Cheering, Whistling ]

971
01:42:11,814 --> 01:42:14,169
Find him. Find him!

972
01:42:14,254 --> 01:42:16,324
How can l find...

973
01:42:16,414 --> 01:42:18,450
this glorious place?

974
01:42:19,454 --> 01:42:22,173
And he said to me:

975
01:42:22,214 --> 01:42:26,002
"A child shall lead you."

976
01:42:27,454 --> 01:42:29,490
A child.

977
01:42:29,534 --> 01:42:31,764
- And behold!
